But now we're going to finally tackle the magic number method. And there are logical steps we need to take to make sure this actually works out but i will explain more once we actually solve a few practice problems.

1. To convert the subnet mask to decimal if necessary because some questions or scenarios you'll encounter they'll take on a binary form
2. Find the "Interesting Octet" = anything that's not 255 or 0, if you see a value that's out of place that's under that category? you got your interesting octet
3. Calculate the Host Range
4. Identify the Network Address
5. Identify the Broadcast Address
6. Get the first usable host address
7. Get the last usable host address

The first practice problem goes like this:
IP address: 165.245.77.14
Subnet Mask: 255.255.240.0

To solve this a solving chart would help us visualize and set a foundational flow as to what's actually going on here. It'd be easy for me to just solve it in paragraph form, but since we're all cave dummies it helps to kind of reinforce the point I'm trying to make here. And we need to do it two times to find the subnet ID(which for solving purposes acts like the Network Address) and then the Broadcast Address.

Solving Chart:

Mask		255.255.240.0
Action
IP		165.245.77.14
Subnet ID	

Now to use this chart we just need to put in our given values first which I've already done and so you can see it sequentially im goin to copy it over and over if you dont mind. Now for first action we'll follow step two which is finding the interesting octet and we achieve that in tandem of writing out our subnet id, so the rule here is if its 255, just copy the ip address and if it's zero then let it be zero

Solving Chart:

Mask		255.255.240.0
Action		Cy  Cy     Ze
IP		165.245.77.14
Subnet ID	165 245    0

Now we know that the octet with the 240 fulfills the conditions of not being either 255 or zero thats our interesting octet. The next thing we have to do is to use this interesting octet as a subtrahend against 256. Now why 256 instead of 255? It's because 256 is 0 to 255, so in numerical form it does end in 255 but the amount of values are 256 since 0 is included. So the answer of 256-240 is 16 and that means there are 16 hosts on this particular subnet and depending on the problem especially if we're still starting out with this or haven't mastered the 7 second yet a reference chart for intervals based on your magic number is necessary

Interval Chart:
0	16	32	48	64	80	96	112	128	144	160	176	192	208	224	240	256

If we look at the ip address number on our interesting octet we will see its 77, this is going to come in important as we can use that value to estimate that our subnet id is between 64 and 79. With that in mind, to figure out the subnet ID we can just take the first number of that range which would be 64 and we would add that into the empty space on our subnet ID row

Solving Chart(eq means equation, cy means copy and ze means zero):

Mask		255.255.240.0
Action		Cy  Cy  eq Ze
IP		165.245.77.14
Subnet ID	165 245 64  0

And there you have it, you finally crunched the subnet id and used the magic number method for the first time, but we're not done with this bs math yet since we also need to figure our the broadcast address:

Solving Chart:
Mask		255.255.240.0
Action
Subnet ID	165.245.64.0
Broadcast
Address

This is the reason why we need to find the subnet ID first, so we can have something to work with when we get to this part. But overall with a few changes, figuring out is part is just as easy as the first one, being faster at it is the grind but that's okay you'll get the hang of it after several tries of different addresses.

To kick things off we have to do things like how we did it before, if its 255 just copy the subnet id, however if its 0 instead of copying zero we substitute for 255, why? because this is the broadcast address and to find the last usable host we just subtract one from this figure just like what we did for classful subnetting. And also, the weird octet out in our subnet mask is the same interesting octet.

Solving Chart(Su means Substitute):
Mask		255.255.240.0
Action		Cy  Cy     Su
Subnet ID	165.245.64.0
Broadcast	165 245   255
Address

Just the same as before,we use the equation of (256-Interesting Octet) to find the magic number which is 16. Now here's how things are a bit different, now we use a different equation we take the Subnet ID in the interesting octet column and then add the magic number to it and then subtract 1. So its 64+16 = 80 - 1 = 79. That's the answer to the missing space on our broadcast address. The reason the equation exists is because addresses starts from zero, so if we just add to get 80 if you check the chart we made we'd already be in the next subnet, but we're trying to find the broadcast for *this* subnet so we subtract one to find the very last address for the block size or magic number

Solving Chart(Su means Substitute):
Mask		255.255.240.0
Action		Cy  Cy     Su
Subnet ID	165.245.64.0
Broadcast	165 245 79 255
Address

And there you have it, we have the subnet id and the broadcast address. To get the first and last usable address we just add plus one to the leftmost octet of the subnet id and subtract one from the broadcast address.

First usable Address - 165.245.64.1
Last usable Address - 165.245.79.254

The second practice problem goes like this:
IP address: 192.168.13.0
Subnet Mask: 255.255.255.240 (/28)
Now this one is a little different from the first problem because the interesting octet is now in the fourth position instead of the third. But the method is exactly the same, so lets get to it.
Solving Chart:
Mask		255.255.255.240
Action		
IP		192.168.13.0
Subnet ID
Just like before we follow the same rules, if its 255 copy the IP and if its 0 let it be zero. The 240 is our interesting octet because its neither 255 nor 0.
Solving Chart:
Mask		255.255.255.240
Action		Cy   Cy   Cy   
IP		192.168.13.0
Subnet ID	192  168  13
Now we calculate the magic number: 256 - 240 = 16. So our interval chart looks like this:
0   16   32   48   64   80   96   112   128   144   160   176   192   208   224   240   256
The fourth octet of our IP address is 0 which sits right at the start of the first interval block between 0 and 15. So our subnet ID for the interesting octet is just 0.
Solving Chart:
Mask		255.255.255.240
Action		Cy   Cy   Cy   Eq
IP		192.168.13.0
Subnet ID	192  168  13   0
Now for the broadcast address we do the same thing as before, copy the subnet ID where its 255 and substitute 255 where its 0. The interesting octet stays as our equation column.
Solving Chart:
Mask		255.255.255.240
Action		Cy   Cy   Cy   Su
Subnet ID	192.168.13.0
Broadcast	192  168  13   255
Address
Now we apply the equation: Subnet ID of interesting octet + magic number - 1. So its 0 + 16 - 1 = 15. That fills in our broadcast address.
Solving Chart:
Mask		255.255.255.240
Action		Cy   Cy   Cy   Su
Subnet ID	192.168.13.0
Broadcast	192  168  13   15
Address
So our final answers are:
Subnet ID:          192.168.13.0
Broadcast Address:  192.168.13.15
First Usable Host:  192.168.13.1
Last Usable Host:   192.168.13.14
And there you have it. Notice how the method did not change at all even though the interesting octet moved to a different position. That is the whole point of the magic number method, once you know the steps it does not matter where the interesting octet is hiding.
